Along the eastern edge of Vancouver Island, British Columbia, numerous sedimentary rocks of the Upper Cretaceous Nanaimo Group contain extensive coal and plant fossil deposits. These diverse macrofloras were studied and described by
				Bell (1957) and
				Dawson (1883,
				1893). However, they have been subject to only limited work since that time (
				Rouse et al. 1971;
				McIver 1994;
				Pearson and Hebda 2006;
				Brink et al. 2009). The southern extent of the Nanaimo Group lies on the northern end of Saanich Peninsula and adjacent to the Gulf Islands just north of Victoria, British Columbia, where numerous plant fossils have been recovered over the last 20 years (
				Fig. 1).

The primary difference between the Comox Formation in the original sense and the Sidney and Barnes Island formations is that the latter are composed of marine facies (
					Haggart et al. 2005), while the former is typically expressed by terrestrial to marginal marine facies (
					Mustard 1994). Previous work associated outcrops at the eastern edge of the study area with a protected embayment, either a barrier island complex or estuary, adjacent to a stormy coast, and they assigned these stratigraphic sections to the Saanich Member (see asterisks in
					Fig. 1;
					Johnstone et al. 2006;
					Johnstone 2006).

The use of morphotypes to describe floras has become a common approach recently due to the difficulty in confidently assigning plant parts to modern taxonomic groups. This approach is becoming standard practice for first descriptions of plant assemblages and museum collections (
					Johnson and Ellis 2002;
					Peppe et al. 2008). The use of morphotyped floras has been largely applied to interpreting paleoclimate through the use of CLAMP analysis (
					Wolfe 1993;
					Craggs 2005;
					Tomsich et al. 2010) and, as we do in this study, paleoecological interpretations (
					Iglesias et al. 2007;
					Tomsich et al. 2010).

The depositional setting of the Saanich Member is informed by Upper Cretaceous records from Greenland and Europe where Platanaceae fossils provide a signal of floodplain environments (
					Boyd 1993;
					Coiffard and Gomez 2010;
					Coiffard et al. 2006). For example,
					Platanus affinis (Lesquereux) Bell (
					Fig. A1
						e
					), which is present in the Saanich Member macroflora, is found to be a characteristical floodplain species in the Upper Cretaceous of Greenland (
					Boyd 1993), and members of Menispermaceae (
					Fig. A1
						e
					) have been associated with Albian floodplains of Europe (
					Coiffard et al. 2007). These studies also correlated gymnosperm diversity and abundance (particularly cycads) with brackish to marine deposits (
					Boyd 1993;
					Coiffard et al. 2012). Taking these observations into consideration, assemblages A1 and A3 are interpreted to reflect growth near wetland to shallow water environments associated with brackish or salt water.
